 A Historical and Contemporary Description and Analysis -- tThe International Joint Commission and the Evolution of the Great Lakes Water Quality Agreement: Accountability, Progress Reporting, and Measuring Performance -- tLegacies -- tFrom “Stakeholder to Rights-Holder”: Re-examining the Role of Indigenous Peoples in the International Joint Commission as the Third Sovereign -- tThe Boundary Waters Treaty, the International Joint Commission, and the Evolution of Transboundary Environmental Law and Governance -- tThe Importance of the International Joint Commission -- tThe International Joint Commission: Continually Evolving Approaches to Conflict Resolution -- tAppendices -- tBoundary Waters Treaty -- tThe Clinton-Gibbons Draft, 1907 -- tList of IJC Commissioners -- tSelected Bibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe International Joint Commission oversees and protects the shared waters of Canada and the United States. Created by the Boundary Waters Treaty of 1909, it is one of the world's oldest international environmental bodies. A pioneering piece of transborder water governance, the IJC has been integral to the modern Canada–United States relationship. This is the definitive history of the International Joint Commission. Separating myth from reality and uncovering the historical evolution of the IJC from its inception to its present, this collection features an impressive interdisciplinary group of scholars and practitioners. Examining the many aspects of border waters from east to west The First Century of the International Joint Commission traces the three major periods of the IJC, detailing its early focus on water flow, its middle period of growth and increasing politicization, and its modern emphasis on ecosystems. Informative, detailed, and fascinating, The First Century of the International Joint Commission is essential reading for academics, contemporary policy makers, governments, and all those interested in sustainability, climate change, pollution, and resiliency along the Canada–US Border.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInternational Joint Commission. 0aInternational lakes. 0aInternational rivers. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh  aBoundary Waters Treaty.  aCanada-United States Border.  aColumbia River.  aGreat Lakes.  aLake systems.  aMilk River.  aSouris River.  aSt. Croix River.  aSt. Lawrence River.  aSt. Mary River.  aair quality.  adams.  adiversions.  aregulation.  ariver systems.  ashared water uses.  ashared water.  atransboundary issues.  awater flow.  awater level.  awater quality.1 aBenidickson, Jamie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandson, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClamen, Murray, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClamen, Murray, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDan Tarlock, A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDenning, Meredith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEttawageshik, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Noah D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Noah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinmiller, B. Timothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeinmiller, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohns, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKenny, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela